	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64604823"><p>There was a massive, vibrant market of small machines at the time, filled with "good enough". The IBM PC was released in August 12, 1981. There were already a multitude of janky, good enough OSs out by that point. CP/M. AMOS, whatever the ZX81 ran, TRSDOS, and so on and so forth. Even unix (unics) was originally a cut down "good enough" take on MULTICS, built for small, obsolete machines.</p><p>Billy didn't invent the concept of "good enough".</p></div>
	</div>

